<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Level crossings</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">Written evidence from</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt"> the Rail Accident Investigation Branch (RAIB)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt"> (SLC 017)</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Summary of main points: </span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 14.17pt; padding-left:7.43pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Over the 8 years since the RAIB has been operational</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> accidents at level crossings in the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> have resulted in 78 fatalities.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 14.17pt; padding-left:7.43pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">During that time the RAIB has started 43 level crossing investigations related to the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">’s mainline railways, and published 35 reports.  These reports have resulted in 130 recommendations for improving level crossing safety</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 14.17pt; padding-left:7.43pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The safety authority for Network Rail’s infrastructure is the Office of Rail Regulation (ORR), and in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Northern Ireland</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, the Department for Regional Affairs (DRA).  These bodies have reported that industry has taken sufficient action to close out 105 rec</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ommendations.  The remaining 25 are reported as work in progress.  The RAIB has been working with the ORR to seek greater visibility of the current status of actions that are planned to be taken in response to those recommendations.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 14.17pt; padding-left:7.43pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Although it is recognis</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ed that Network Rail is addressing many of the issues identified by the RAIB, there remain a number of areas of particular concern.  These include: influencing user behaviour at level crossings; risk assessment of level crossings, including consideration o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">f local factors; and design and equipment.  It is important to the improvement of safety that sufficient finance, resource and management attention is deployed to drive the recommended actions through to completion in a timely fashion.</span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 24pt; text-indent:-24pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 24pt; text-indent:-24pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Q1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Are current safe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ty measures at level crossings adequate?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">RAIB investigations and recommendations</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">: </span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 14.17pt; padding-left:14.18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The railway industry is working to reduce the risk of collisions between trains and level crossing users.  Nevertheless, over the last eight years such accidents on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Great B</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ritain</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">’s mainline railways have resulted in 77 fatalities and one fatality in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Northern </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Ireland</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  Currently, level crossings account for about 7.7%</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of the total risk </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">(excluding suicide) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">on the mainline railway infrastructure (excluding Northern Ireland).  </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 14.17pt; padding-left:14.18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The RAIB investigates accidents at level crossings where it judges there are likely to be significant safety lessons for the railway industry.  Although, in general, the RAIB will not investigate accidents that have resulted from deliberate misuse by user</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s, it may investigate such cases if it considers that the design or operation of the crossing may have given rise to the misuse (eg long waiting times at a user worked crossing) or if the consequences of the accident warrant investigation (eg consideration</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of the crashworthiness of rolling stock).</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 14.17pt; padding-left:14.18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The RAIB notes that the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">’s mainline railway has a good overall level crossing safety record relative to the other European Union Member States.  However, between October 2005 (when the RAIB became operational) and 1 September 2013, the RAIB considered that 43 level crossing accid</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ents and incidents warranted investigation because of the particular safety issues involved, and it has published 35 reports (including three bulletins, and two ‘class investigations’ that considered safety at specific types of level crossing).  See </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Ta</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ble </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1 for details.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 14.17pt; padding-left:14.18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The RAIB has made 130 recommendations to improve safety at level crossings on the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">’s mainline network.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 14.17pt; padding-left:14.18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Some key issues that are still of concern to the RAIB are described in the following paragraphs.  Details of the areas of recommendati</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ons already made by the RAIB to address these issues are provided at Table 2, along with a summary of the actions reported being taken by the railway industry in response.</span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Areas of concern: means of influencing user behaviour at level crossings </span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 20.29pt; padding-left:8.06pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The railwa</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">y industry aims to influence user behaviour at level crossings by various means, including active measures such as stop lights, and passive measures such as signage and the provision of telephones.  Other factors influencing human behaviour (eg distraction</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">) can result in these measures becoming ineffective.  Accordingly, the RAIB has made recommendations for measures which might better influence the safe behaviour of crossing users (for details see paragraphs </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">19</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">21</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">23</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, and T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">able 2 (items a-e and h-j) and is supportive of ongoing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">RSSB</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> research into issues concerning the safety of pedestrians at footpath and pedestrian crossings.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 20.29pt; padding-left:8.06pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In eight investigations the RAIB has expressed concerns about </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">passive crossings where users had an inadequate warning of approaching trains due to limited sighting</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  For details of the relevant RAIB recommendation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and actions rep</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">orted as taken in response</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> see T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">able 2(b).</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 20.29pt; padding-left:8.06pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In only three of the accidents investigated </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">has it been proved that the cause was a deliberate violation of the rules associated with the use of the crossing.  In four other investigations a deliberate violation </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">may</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> have played a part in the causation of the accident.  </span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Areas of concern: Risk assess</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">ment at level crossings</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 20.29pt; padding-left:8.06pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">To manage risk effectively, the railway needs to assess risk at each crossing and identify those where the risk is highest.  It should then identify potential measures to improve safety and assess their practicability.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 20.29pt; padding-left:8.06pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In 20 of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">35 RAIB level crossing investigations it was found that the industry’s application of the risk assessment process had been deficient and/or the findings of the risk assessment had not been fully implemented.  The RAIB findings include:</span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 3pt 48.2pt; text-indent:-16.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">a.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">errors made during d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ata collection and risk assessments (eg incorrect data); </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 3pt 48.2pt; text-indent:-16.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">b.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">inadequate consideration of local factors at individual crossings;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 3pt 48.2pt; text-indent:-16.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">c.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">competence of risk assessors and crossing inspectors;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 3pt 48.2pt; text-indent:-16.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">d.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">actions not being taken in response to inspection and risk assessments; </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 3pt 48.2pt; text-indent:-16.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">e.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">inse</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nsitivity of the All Level Crossing Risk Model</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to certain inputs (eg sighting times); and</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 3pt 48.2pt; text-indent:-16.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">f.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">incorrect assessment of sighting distance</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 20.29pt; padding-left:8.06pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">For details of relevant </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">RAIB </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">recommendations and of actions reported as taken </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in response </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">by the railway industry, see </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ble 2(k). </span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Areas of concern: Assessment of local factors </span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 20.29pt; padding-left:8.06pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Although the risk of human error at level crossings cannot be totally eradicated, there are often measures that can be made to mitigate the risk.  The railway therefore needs to have sufficient competent staff to identify, and correctly assess, not only th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e risk associated with the more generic features of the crossing but also the local factors.  This </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">should be subject of supervision and checking.  Examples of factors identified in RAIB investigations include:  </span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">At passive level crossings</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:9pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 45.94pt; padding-left:14.06pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">limited warning</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of approaching trains due to obstructed sightlines (eg vegetation);</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:9pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 45.94pt; padding-left:14.06pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">lack of visual cues prompting users to look for trains at the optimum point on their approach to the crossing;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:9pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 45.94pt; padding-left:14.06pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the effect of sunlight or darkness on the visibility of approaching trains;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:9pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 45.94pt; padding-left:14.06pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">significant usage by vulnerable users; </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:9pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 45.94pt; padding-left:14.06pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">seasonal variation in the use of a level crossing (eg harvesting); and</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:9pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 45.94pt; padding-left:14.06pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">history of near-misses and misuse (eg gates left open).</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">At active level crossings</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:9pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 45.94pt; padding-left:14.06pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the effect of sunlight and background illumination on the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">conspicuity of road traffic signals;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:9pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 45.94pt; padding-left:14.06pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the luminance of road traffic signals;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:9pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 45.94pt; padding-left:14.06pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">potential distraction of drivers by road signs and at junctions; </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:9pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 45.94pt; padding-left:14.06pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">local road traffic conditions;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:9pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 45.94pt; padding-left:14.06pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a history of near-misses and misuse; and</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:9pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 45.94pt; padding-left:14.06pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the potential for accidents to be caused b</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">y human error at crossings operated by railway staff.</span></li><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 20.29pt; padding-left:8.06pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">For details of relevant </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">RAIB </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">recommendations and of actions reported as taken </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in response </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">by the railway industry, see </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">able 2(k). </span></li></ol></ul><p style="margin:6pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Areas of concern: Design and equipment</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 20.29pt; padding-left:8.06pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The RAIB’s investigations have </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">identified a range of technical issues that have been factors in accidents at level crossings.  </span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Locating trains in long sections </span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 20.29pt; padding-left:8.06pt; text-indent:0pt"><a name="_Ref366698882"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">On some rural lines there are long signal sections that do not have equipment that identifies the location of a train.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Consequently, when phoned by an intending user of a crossing (eg a farmer with tractor and trailer) signallers are unable to confirm the exact position of the train and must ask the user to wait.  This results in long delays to users and generates a risk o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">f misuse (Penrhyndeudraeth B7/2010 &amp; Sudbury 14/2011)</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  For details of the relevant RAIB recommendation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and actions rep</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">orted as taken in response </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">by the railway industry, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">see T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">able 2(d).</span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Lack of engineered safeguards</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 20.29pt; padding-left:8.06pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The RAIB’s investigation following a f</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">atal accident at Moreton-on-Lugg in 2010 found that the crossing did not have equipment to prevent the signaller from setting the protecting signal at danger and then immediately raising the barriers before the arrival of the train at the crossing.  It was</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> subsequently discovered that another 97 crossings with protecting signals also lacked such a safeguard.  Although actions are in hand to remedy all of the above crossings, Network Rail has informed the RAIB that there are another 48 crossings where there </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is no protecting signal and no engineered safeguard to prevent a single human error leading to the road being open to traffic before a train arrives at the crossing.  For details of the relevant RAIB recommendation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and actions reported as taken in respons</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">by the railway industry</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> see </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">able 2(f).</span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Safety of Automatic Open Crossings (locally monitored)</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 20.29pt; padding-left:8.06pt; text-indent:0pt"><a name="_Ref366698926"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In 2012, the RAIB published a report on the safety of Automatic Open Crossings (locally monitored) – AOCLs.  This type of crossing is protected by road traf</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">fic signals which flash red when trains are approaching, but has no barriers or gates.  The report concluded that on a per-crossing basis, AOCLs are the highest risk form of level crossing to be found on public roads crossed by the main line railway networ</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">k in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Great Britain</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  They have also had the highest number of collisions between trains and road vehicles.  </span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">For details of the relevant RAIB recommendations and actions reported as taken in response</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">by the railway industry</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> see </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">able 2(h).</span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Conspicuity of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">stop lights</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 20.29pt; padding-left:8.06pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The safety of most active level crossings is critically dependent on the conspicuity of the stop lights.  Two RAIB investigations have identified the need for the railway industry to investigate ways of improving the conspicuity of ‘miniature s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">top lights’ used at some footpath and user worked crossings.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 20.29pt; padding-left:8.06pt; text-indent:0pt"><a name="_Ref366698947"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Another factor influencing the conspicuity of stop lights at level crossings is sunlight.  When the sun shines directly onto a light unit it can cause an effect known as ‘wash-out’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> which can o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">bscure the illumination.  In other cases</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the sun shining from behind the lights into the eyes of users can make it difficult for the user to discern that a light is showing.  In both cases, the loss of conspicuity due to sunlight can be exacerbated if the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> lamps and/or the lens produce too low a light output (as was the case in the fatal accidents at Wraysholme in November 2008 and Beech Hill in December 2012).</span></a></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 24pt; text-indent:-24pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 24pt; text-indent:-24pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Q2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">How should they be improved?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Areas of RAIB recommendations related to level crossings</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 20.29pt; padding-left:8.06pt; text-indent:0pt"><a name="_Ref366706004"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Areas o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">f RAIB recommendations published</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in recent years are listed in T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">able 2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> along with a summary of the RAIB’s understanding of the actions being taken by the railway industry in response (as reported to the RAIB by ORR).  In three of these areas the RAIB is s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">till awaiting to be informed of the actions that are proposed.  In all other areas:</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 72pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">–</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the RAIB is still awaiting final confirmation from the ORR that it considers that the actions taken are complete and sufficient; or </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 72pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">–</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">full resolution of the issue addressed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> by the recommendation is dependent on the outcome of ongoing research or trials.</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 24pt; text-indent:-24pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 24pt; text-indent:-24pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Q3</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">In addition to bridges and underpasses what other cost-effective measures can be introduced to replace or improve safety at level crossings? </span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 20.29pt; padding-left:8.06pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The RAIB’s recommendations </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">all outline measures that will improve safety.  For the primary areas of improvement sought by these recommendations please refer to the answer to question 2.</span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 24pt; text-indent:-24pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 24pt; text-indent:-24pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Q4</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">How should expenditure on improving safety at level crossings be prioritised in relation to o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ther demands on the rail budget? </span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 20.29pt; padding-left:8.06pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The duty holder (in these cases the owner of the level crossing) is obliged by law to reduce the risk at level crossings so far as is reasonably practicable.  The assessment of potential measures for improvement will often</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> include an analysis of cost and benefit.  However, the RAIB’s investigations have found that the processes, tools and techniques </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">for assessing risk have been in need of improvement.  It should also be noted that in many cases the safety of crossings can b</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e improved, without significant capital investment, by addressing the factors that are likely to influence the behaviour of users.  This requires level crossing managers to have detailed understanding of the risk at each crossing and the competence to iden</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">tify practical measures for improvement.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 20.29pt; padding-left:8.06pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">For all the RAIB’s recommendations the duty holder is obliged by law to explain to the relevant safety authority (the ORR in most cases) the actions it intends to take, and its timescales for doing so. This explanat</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ion should be based on a careful evaluation of the recommendation and the measures to be taken in response.  The relevant safety authority</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> is required to assess the adequacy of the duty holder’s response, and where this is considered insufficient, to take</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> appropriate action. </span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 24pt; text-indent:-24pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 24pt; text-indent:-24pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Q5</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Is Network Rail giving sufficient priority to improving safety at level crossings? </span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 20.29pt; padding-left:8.06pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The RAIB observes that Network Rail has managed to close around 10% of all its level crossings since 2009 and the recent ORR report</span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> stat</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">es</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> that N</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">etwork Rail is on-target to meet its 25% reduction in level crossing risk over Control Period 4 (CP4) 2009-14, as measured by its own model.  The RAIB is also aware that Network Rail’s Strategic Business Plan covering the period 2014-19 includes reference </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to a ring-fenced fund of £77 million for expenditure at crossings (this is in addition to the normal budget provision for the management and renewal of crossings) and a commitment to work towards the closure of at least 30 high risk crossings as part of an</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> ongoing strategy to reduce risk still further. </span><span style="color:#00ffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 20.29pt; padding-left:8.06pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The RAIB understands that some recommendations will take time to implement.  Nevertheless, it is important to the improvement of safety that sufficient finance, resource and management attention is deployed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to drive the recommended actions through to completion in a thorough and timely fashion.</span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 24pt; text-indent:-24pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 24pt; text-indent:-24pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Q6</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Is Government policy and regulatory action by the Office of Rail Regulation (ORR) in relation to safety at level crossings adequate? What more should the Governme</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">nt and ORR do?</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span></p><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 20.29pt; padding-left:8.06pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The RAIB notes the work undertaken by the ORR to follow up with railway duty holders the actions that are planned and taken in response to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the RAIB’s </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">recommendations.  The ORR and DRA have reported to the RAIB that it is considered that th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e industry has taken sufficient action to close out 105 of the 130 recommendations that the RAIB has made in relation to level crossings.  The remaining 25 are classed as work in progress.  Of these, ten have been open for more than two years.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 20.29pt; padding-left:8.06pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The RAIB i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s currently working with the ORR and Network Rail to secure greater ongoing visibility of the current safety initiatives related to level crossings and programmes for completion, and to better understand how the actions taken or planned relate to the RAIB’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s recommendations.  This would help the RAIB to better understand how the risks identified are being managed and so inform subsequent investigation activity.  </span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 24pt; text-indent:-24pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 24pt; text-indent:-24pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 24pt; text-indent:-24pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Q7</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">How should the legislation governing level crossings be updated?</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span></p><ol start="32" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="32" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 20.29pt; padding-left:8.06pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The RAIB had input to an</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">d supports the proposals that were made in the Law Commissions’ consultation document, particularly those that have the potential to streamline and simplify the process for closing level crossings when this is necessary to improve public safety, and the fo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">stering of co-operation between interested parties.  The RAIB also supports the need to review the existing legal structures for defining signage in use at public and private level crossings</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  This should</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> facilitate the updating of signs to modern standard</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s of clarity and accessibility </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">give all users clear information on how to use the crossing safely.  The Law Commissions’ proposals related to new road traffic offences and increased penalties for violations are also welcomed.</span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:6pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 24pt; text-indent:-24pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Q8</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">How should public awareness of safety at level crossings be improved? </span></p><ol start="33" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="33" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:ArialMT; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18.75pt; padding-left:9.6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In two of the RAIB’s investigations</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the use of headphones has been identified as a possible factor that may have prevented people from being aware of the approach of trains.  The RAIB </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is therefore supportive of Network Rail’s campaigns to promote safe behaviour at level crossings (and elsewhere on the railway).  In particular, the RAIB notes: the recent television campaign to educate the public on the safe use of footpath level crossing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s; the website (</span><a href="http://www.rail-life.co.uk"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">www.rail-life.co.uk</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">) to promote safe behaviour of young people; and t</span><span style="font-family:ArialMT; font-size:12pt">he campaign called ‘Lose Your Headphones, not your life’ launched by Network Rail in August 2012 to persuade young people to remove their headphones at level crossings.  </span></li><li style="font-family:ArialMT; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18.75pt; padding-left:9.6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:ArialMT; font-size:12pt">The RAIB expects that ongoing RSSB research into the safety of footpath </span><span style="font-family:ArialMT; font-size:12pt">and user work</span><span style="font-family:ArialMT; font-size:12pt">ed crossings (see T</span><span style="font-family:ArialMT; font-size:12pt">able 2(c)) will include consideration of the ways that intending users can be made aware of how to use crossings safely by the provision of signage, or other visual cues to look and listen for approaching trains.</span></li></ol></ol></div><br style="clear:both; mso-break-type:section-break; page-break-before:always" /><div><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Table 1-RAIB investigations by type of level crossing (including </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Northern Ireland</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic"> but excluding heritage and tramways)</span></p><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:0pt; width:521.4pt"><tr><td style="background-color:#99ccff; border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.