ntends that individual managers will take full responsibility for the safety of each crossing and will develop a detailed appreciation of the safety issues at each.</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:132pt"><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 5pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The RAIB supports th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">e initiative and awaits with interest Network Rail’s evaluation of the affect on the quality of level crossing management.</span></p></td></tr></tbody><!--[if !supportMisalignedColumns]><tr style="height:0pt"><td style="width:29.4pt; border:none"></td><td style="width:156pt; border:none"></td><td style="width:204pt; border:none"></td><td style="width:132pt; border:none"></td></tr><![endif]--></table><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 5pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt"> All information </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">in this submission </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">concerning RAIB reports and recommendations relate only to the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">’s mainline railways. The RAIB has also investigated a number of accidents involving level crossings on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">h</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">eritage railways and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">ramways. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt"> Based on data provided by the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">RSSB</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">’s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt"> Annual Safety Performance Report 2012-13.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt"> The All Level C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">rossing Risk Model (A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">LCRM)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt"> is a tool used by the industry that allows the level of risk to be estimated at an individual level crossing. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a href="#_ftnref4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt"> The ‘sighting distance’ is the distance from the crossing at which approaching trains first come into view</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn5"></a><a href="#_ftnref5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; vertical-align:baseline">Passive crossings: no warning of a train’s approach is given other than by the train driver who may use the train horn. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; vertical-align:baseline">The onus is on the road user or pedestrian to determine whether or not it is safe to cross the line.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; vertical-align:baseline"> Instructions for proper use must </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; vertical-align:baseline">be provided at each location, along with other appropriate signage.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn6"></a><a href="#_ftnref6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt"> Active crossings: the road vehicle or pedestrian is warned of the approach of a train through closure of gates or barriers and/or by stop lights and/or alarms.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn7"></a><a href="#_ftnref7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">Regulation 12 of the Rai</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">lways (Accident Investigation and Reporting) Regulations 2005</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn8"></a><a href="#_ftnref8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> ORR Health and Safety Report 2013 (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">http://www.rail-reg.gov.uk/upload/pdf/health-safety-report-2013.pdf</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn9"></a><a href="#_ftnref9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt"> In this investigation it was found that the train horn was not always audible to pedes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">trians at the crossing</span></p></body></html>